  <Subject Subject_ID="300265002">
    <Parent_Relationships>
      <Preferred_Parent>
        <Parent_Subject_ID>300265001</Parent_Subject_ID>
        <Relationship_Type>Parent/Child</Relationship_Type>
        <Historic_Flag>Current</Historic_Flag>
        <Parent_String>skyphoi [300265001], drinking vessels [300194567], vessels for serving and consuming food [300198938], containers for serving and consuming food [300198760], culinary containers [300197577], containers by function or context [300197200], containers (receptacles) [300197197], Containers (hierarchy name) [300045611], Furnishings and Equipment (hierarchy name) [300264551], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Refers to a type of skyphos that is easily distinguished by its disparate handles, one horizontal and one vertical. The body is similar to that of type A skyphoi but with the lower body more tapered and the foot smaller. They are almost always decorated with an owl, often in red-figure.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000046899/Clark, Elston and Hart, Understanding Greek Vases (2002)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000046786/Getty Museum, Authority file (2003-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Verwijst naar een type skyphoi dat gemakkelijk te herkennen is aan de ongelijke handvatten, één horizontaal en één verticaal. De buik is soortgelijk aan die van skyphoi type A maar met een meer taps toelopend onderste gedeelte en een kleinere voet. Ze zijn bijna altijd versierd met een uil, vaak roodfigurig.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>雙耳大杯的類型，以其不相同的握把為特色，一側握把為水平、另一側則為垂直，杯身與A型雙環大杯類似，但杯身下部較尖細，杯座也較小。此類型的杯子幾乎都以貓頭鷹為飾，且通常為紅繪式。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Bezeichnet eine Form des Skyphos, die sich leicht an den unterschiedlichen Griffen erkennen lässt: ein Griff ist horizontal, der andere vertikal. Der Körper hat eine ähnliche Form wie Skyphos Typ A, aber mit einer stärkeren Verjüngung zum Fuß hin und einem kleineren Fuß. Die Bemalung ist fast immer eine Eule, meist rotfigurig.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
